PAUSE: Complete Product Specification & Implementation Plan
Executive Summary
Pause is a zero-barrier progressive web application designed to interrupt addictive impulses in real-time. Unlike traditional recovery apps that track streaks, days clean, or money saved, Pause operates on a fundamentally different psychological principle: recovery isn't about maintaining a perfect record—it's about surviving the next five minutes.
The app introduces deliberate cognitive friction through four escalating gates that force the brain to shift from impulsive craving to logical evaluation, effectively breaking the dopamine loop before the user acts on their addiction.
Problem Statement
The Flaw in Current Recovery Apps
Most addiction recovery applications rely on gamification mechanics: streak counters, badges, "days clean" trackers, and cumulative savings calculators. While these features provide short-term motivation, they create a critical psychological vulnerability:
The Shame Spiral Effect
User maintains a 47-day streak
User experiences a craving and relapses on day 48
The app displays: "Streak broken: 0 days"
User experiences intense shame and guilt
Shame triggers a binge: "I already ruined my streak, might as well go all the way"
User abandons the app entirely
This is a well-documented phenomenon in addiction psychology. The very tool meant to support recovery becomes a source of trauma when the inevitable slip occurs.
The Real Need
What users need in the moment of crisis is not a reminder of their past failures or a pressure to maintain perfection. They need:
Immediate intervention - something to occupy the critical 5-minute window where most impulsive decisions are made
Cognitive disruption - a way to break the neurological craving loop
Zero judgment - an experience that doesn't track, score, or shame
Universal applicability - a tool that works for any addiction (gambling, drinking, shopping, doomscrolling, substance use)
Solution Overview
Core Philosophy
"Recovery isn't a high score. It's just getting through the next five minutes."
Pause treats every urge as an isolated incident. The app has no memory of past successes or failures. It doesn't care if this is the user's first craving or their fiftieth. Its only function is to help them survive this specific moment.
The Four-Gate Intervention System
When a user feels an urge, they tap a single button and enter a sequential pipeline of four cognitive/physical challenges. Each gate is designed to activate different neural pathways, progressively shifting the brain from the amygdala (emotional/impulsive center) to the prefrontal cortex (logical/executive function).
Gate 1: The Reality Anchor (Time Theft)
Forces logical evaluation of the immediate cost
Shifts brain from emotional craving to cost-benefit analysis
Gate 2: Sensory Override (Stroop Effect)
Creates severe cognitive interference
Forces prefrontal cortex to override amygdala
Gate 3: Decay Matrix (Working Memory)
Visualizes the fading nature of urges
Engages visuospatial working memory
Gate 4: Physical Grounding (Breath & Hold)
Activates parasympathetic nervous system
Transitions brain from high-beta (panic) to alpha (calm) waves
The Zero-Score Dashboard
The home screen is intentionally minimalist:
No streaks
No calendars
No "days clean" counters
No money saved metrics
No progress graphs
Instead, it features:
A single, tactile "Pause" button
A "Future Self Vault" where users write notes to their panicked future selves
A calming, social-media-inspired dark mode interface
