The Four Gates: Detailed Mechanics
Gate 1: The Reality Anchor (Time Theft)
Objective: Shift the brain from emotional craving to logical cost-benefit analysis.
Psychological Basis:
Addiction operates on immediate gratification. The brain focuses entirely on the short-term relief, ignoring long-term consequences. This gate forces the user to confront the immediate cost of their action in concrete terms.
Why Time Instead of Money?
Money can feel abstract or guilt-inducing
Time is universally understood and finite
Everyone has the same 24 hours
Time theft applies to all addictions (gambling, drinking, shopping, doomscrolling)
No cumulative tracking = no shame when broken
Mechanics:
User sees a large, tactile slider
Prompt: "If you give in right now, how much of your day will this consume?"
Range: 1 hour to 12 hours
User slides to quantify the "time theft"
App displays reality check: "You are about to trade X hours of your life for 5 minutes of relief."
Example Scenarios:
Drinker: "Half a day" (the act, the hangover, the lost productivity)
Gambler: "The whole weekend" (the binge, the recovery, the financial stress)
Doomscroller: "3 hours of sleep" (the lost rest, the next-day fatigue)
Shopper: "4 hours" (the browsing, the purchase, the buyer's remorse)
