Gate 2: Sensory Override (Stroop Effect)
Objective: Create severe cognitive interference that forces the prefrontal cortex to override the amygdala.
Psychological Basis:
The Stroop Effect is a well-documented psychological phenomenon where naming the color of a word is slower and more error-prone when the word itself spells a different color (e.g., the word "RED" printed in blue ink). This creates cognitive interference that requires executive function to resolve.
Why This Works for Addiction:
Cravings activate the amygdala (emotional/impulsive center)
The Stroop task requires the prefrontal cortex (logical/executive center)
The brain cannot maintain intense craving while solving cognitive interference
It literally "overrides" the impulse with logic
Mechanics:
Large word appears on screen (e.g., "DRINK", "BUY", "WAIT", "BREATHE")
Word is colored (Red, Blue, Green, Yellow)
Four color buttons appear below
User must tap the COLOR of the text, not the word
Must complete 5 rounds correctly
Incorrect answer resets to round 1
Example:
Word: "DRINK" (colored BLUE)
Correct answer: Tap "BLUE" button
Incorrect answer: Tap "DRINK" (if it were a color option)
Accessibility Considerations:
High contrast colors
Large tap targets (minimum 44x44px)
Clear visual feedback
No time pressure (user can take as long as needed)
