Gate 3: Decay Matrix (Working Memory)
Objective: Engage visuospatial working memory while visually demonstrating that urges fade over time.
Psychological Basis:
Working memory is the brain's ability to hold and manipulate information over short periods. By taxing this system, we further distract from the craving. The "decay" mechanic provides a powerful visual metaphor: just as the blocks fade, so does the urge.
Why This Works for Addiction:
Urges follow a wave pattern: they peak, then fade
Most people don't realize this - they think the craving will last forever
Visualizing the decay reinforces the truth: "This will pass if I wait"
Engages a different neural pathway (visuospatial sketchpad)
Mechanics:
3x3 grid of blocks appears
3 random blocks light up (solid color)
After 1 second, blocks begin to fade (not disappear instantly)
Over 2 seconds, blocks gradually become transparent
User must tap the 3 blocks that lit up
Must complete 3 rounds correctly
Incorrect answer resets to round 1
The Decay Effect:
Blocks don't just vanish
They slowly fade from 100% opacity to 20% opacity over 2 seconds
User must hold the spatial pattern in memory as visual cues degrade
This mimics how cravings work: the intensity fades if you don't act on it
