Disadvantages & Mitigations
Disadvantage 1: "How do I track long-term progress?"
Risk: Users may want to see their improvement over time.
Mitigation:
Explain that long-term progress is tracked by therapists, journals, or personal reflection
This app is an emergency brake, not a fitness tracker
The "Future Self" notes provide qualitative progress tracking
You don't check your odometer while slamming on the brakes
Disadvantage 2: "The gates feel like a game"
Risk: Users might not take the intervention seriously.
Mitigation:
Strict UI rules: no bright colors, no confetti, no "level up" text
Clinical, calm typography and spacing
No sound effects for "winning"
Feels like a medical device, not a mobile game
Disadvantage 3: "What if I fail a gate?"
Risk: Users might get frustrated and close the app.
Mitigation:
No "game over" state
Failed gates simply reset to round 1
User can retry indefinitely
After 3 failures, app suggests skipping to breathing exercise
Prioritizes user safety over game mechanics
Disadvantage 4: "PWA installation is confusing on iOS"
Risk: Users might not know how to install the app.
Mitigation:
App works perfectly in-browser (no installation required)
Only show "Add to Home Screen" prompt after first successful intervention
Provide clear, simple instructions
Fallback to in-browser experience is seamless
Disadvantage 5: "The time theft input feels arbitrary"
Risk: Users might not know how to quantify the time cost.
Mitigation:
Provide example scenarios in onboarding
Make it clear that any estimate is valid
The act of estimating itself is the intervention (forces logical thinking)
Slider is fast and tactile (takes <2 seconds)
